00:32:32,081 --> 00:32:43,585
Want to use my time to explain my support for looking into this proposal, my support for achieving pay equity between the city council and school committee, my view on what this proposal is and what it isn't.

487
00:32:45,956 --> 00:33:05,348
I do not believe that this is in any way incompatible with what I think has been a core and shared goal of the City Council, at least in the one term that I've been a part of it, which is supporting all of our public school employees, supporting Medford Public Schools, and trying to ever improve the conditions of everybody that touches our public school systems.

488
00:33:05,408 --> 00:33:08,209
The students, their families, the teachers, the paras.

489
00:33:09,232 --> 00:33:15,140
all of the workers in our schools that help students and students' families thrive.

490
00:33:15,200 --> 00:33:19,866
I do not believe that this proposal is incompatible with that shared goal whatsoever.

491
00:33:20,287 --> 00:33:21,429
I think that this

492
00:33:24,056 --> 00:33:31,197
the equity between the school committee and the city council is something that I've wanted to, that I've hoped to have the opportunity to vote on ever since I first took office.

493
00:33:32,458 --> 00:33:33,638
These are two elected bodies.

494
00:33:34,118 --> 00:33:35,998
I know how hard we work.

495
00:33:36,018 --> 00:33:39,819
I have some glimmer of perspective of how hard the school committee works.

496
00:33:40,299 --> 00:33:41,660
They have responsibilities that we don't.

497
00:33:42,140 --> 00:33:45,380
I think it is outdated that our bodies are paid differently.

498
00:33:46,060 --> 00:33:49,641
That is the core reason for my support for this proposal.

499
00:33:50,181 --> 00:33:53,822
And even if it were to stop right there, that would be enough for me.

500
00:33:54,802 --> 00:34:06,407
But I see that this draws in a larger conversation about what we can and can't do in Medford, what we have and haven't done in Medford so far, especially every June during budget cycle and really all year round.

501
00:34:06,427 --> 00:34:18,032
If you watch the city council meetings, if you watch the school committee meetings, we are constantly talking about the resources that are afforded to Medford public schools, the people that work in them and everybody that experiences the work that is done in those buildings.

502
00:34:18,953 --> 00:34:24,155
And we are constantly in this conversation about why aren't we doing better and how can we continue to do better

503
00:34:24,659 --> 00:34:30,824
to better value and better resource what goes on in the schools, and better value and better resource the people that do the work of the schools.

504
00:34:32,785 --> 00:34:40,171
This proposal, I think, has brought up those values and those feelings and that imperative that we have to keep doing better.

505
00:34:41,252 --> 00:34:46,576
What I don't believe is that this is an either-or, and what I don't believe is that this is a zero-sum game.

506
00:34:47,797 --> 00:34:53,141
I know that if this proposal were to go forward even as written before amendments,

507
00:34:54,221 --> 00:35:03,488
This is not, this would not take from the same bucket of money that would otherwise go to the workers that contribute to MPS students experience.

508
00:35:03,888 --> 00:35:06,290
Hang on, please.

509
00:35:08,471 --> 00:35:09,832
Thank you, thank you for letting me speak.

510
00:35:12,915 --> 00:35:20,540
This year, we found out that we had a 25 million sum of certified free cash, $25 million.

511
00:35:24,670 --> 00:35:37,061
When we talk about what we can and can't do in Medford and what we have and haven't done, I think that we need to stay, I try to stay, laser focused on what our real opponent is.

512
00:35:38,082 --> 00:35:40,204
Our real opponent is austerity budgeting.

513
00:35:41,024 --> 00:35:50,533
I believe that we have the money to value the people who choose to nominate themselves for school committee and go through the process of running and seek election and serve in that role.

514
00:35:52,674 --> 00:35:58,897
that we have the resources, that we can marshal the resources to do better by everybody who contributes to the Medford public school system.

515
00:36:00,017 --> 00:36:01,218
We talk about it all year long.

516
00:36:02,538 --> 00:36:12,363
We talk about how little authority the school committee, sorry, we talk about where the city council's authority lies and doesn't lie when it comes to making direct appropriations to our budgets, including the school budgets.

517
00:36:12,383 --> 00:36:13,003
We talk about this.

518
00:36:13,823 --> 00:36:15,524
all the time, often in great frustration.

519
00:36:16,064 --> 00:36:19,806
We don't have the power to influence bargaining units here in the city council.

520
00:36:19,846 --> 00:36:24,548
We don't have the authority to make appropriations whatsoever that is out of our purview.

521
00:36:25,228 --> 00:36:36,194
I know, speaking for myself, there's been countless times when I wished it was in our purview, because I'm so frustrated by what I see in the line items in the budgets that we have to vote yes or no on, because that's all that we can do on those budgets.

522
00:36:37,734 --> 00:36:38,935
So when it comes back to this proposal,

523
00:36:39,662 --> 00:36:45,807
Due to the constraints of our jurisdiction here, this is something that we are legally allowed to vote on.

524
00:36:46,587 --> 00:36:51,331
And there are many things that we will never have the opportunity to vote on, because that is not within our purview.

525
00:36:52,072 --> 00:36:58,617
When something comes in front of me that is an opportunity to discuss and interrogate, is this an opportunity to do a good thing?

526
00:36:58,637 --> 00:37:00,779
I want to take that opportunity.

527
00:37:01,219 --> 00:37:04,702
And I do not think it is in any way incompatible with continuing to do better.

528
00:37:05,834 --> 00:37:09,297
in the many areas, the many school-related areas where we need to keep doing better.

529
00:37:10,057 --> 00:37:11,699
It's not a zero-sum, and it's not an either-or.

530
00:37:12,239 --> 00:37:26,270
I look forward to hearing the discussion tonight, and I look forward to continuing to hold ourselves accountable to do this right, and to do right by all of our public employees, and to do as many things right as we can, all at the same time.

531
00:37:26,430 --> 00:37:28,332
And I don't think that we have to choose between one or the other.

532
00:37:28,812 --> 00:37:29,112
Thank you.

533
00:37:30,393 --> 00:37:31,474
Thank you, Councilor Collins.

534
00:37:31,554 --> 00:37:32,455
Councilor Scarpelli.

535
00:37:34,056 --> 00:37:34,337
Thank you.

536
00:37:35,560 --> 00:37:36,321
Council Vice President.

537
00:37:38,062 --> 00:37:46,148
I'm gonna speak as someone who no one else in this council had the opportunity to do.

538
00:37:46,188 --> 00:37:51,032
That's someone that both sat on the school committee seat and in the city council seat.

539
00:37:51,833 --> 00:38:00,780
And understanding, I'll give you my opinion, then I'm gonna share a lot of emails, phone calls, conversations I've had in the last few days.

540
00:38:01,380 --> 00:38:03,002
And I think they're very telling.

541
00:38:04,718 --> 00:38:12,682
When you decide to take the chance and the responsibility of becoming an elected official, it's being elected official.

542
00:38:14,383 --> 00:38:16,664
It's truly a position of service.

543
00:38:18,485 --> 00:38:22,526
You're doing it for a reason other than the paycheck.

544
00:38:23,087 --> 00:38:23,947
I've never looked at it.

545
00:38:28,849 --> 00:38:33,872
Now, as I grew up in this city,

546
00:38:35,256 --> 00:38:38,978
I took it upon myself to watch people that led the way for us.

547
00:38:39,778 --> 00:38:57,288
And they gave back in service, whether it's coaching little league teams, whether it's volunteering at the food bank, whether it's joining a school committee that didn't make any money, or whether it's taking the leap to the city council, because you think you could make more of a difference.

548
00:38:59,144 --> 00:39:11,455
So I generally, personally feel that understanding the process of a pay structure being a major issue, I think it's sad.

549
00:39:11,535 --> 00:39:13,097
I think it's sad to look at it that way.

550
00:39:13,497 --> 00:39:23,966
To think that I had one phone call that said that understanding that we can get better candidates if we pay, that's sad even to think of.

551
00:39:24,972 --> 00:39:29,959
Imagine, imagine voting in people that are there for the money.

552
00:39:31,181 --> 00:39:33,144
That's horrifically frightening to me.

553
00:39:34,628 --> 00:39:42,612
As we move forward, what I found very, very glaring in this situation, the issue of gender equity in pay.

554
00:39:43,413 --> 00:39:59,822
And we received a dialogue from three female school kid members that knew nothing about this, that didn't want anything to do with this vote and think that they're totally against it on the record.

555
00:40:01,123 --> 00:40:03,084
There were two members that didn't reach out to me.

556
00:40:04,178 --> 00:40:05,539
two members that didn't reach out.

557
00:40:07,619 --> 00:40:14,282
And there were two members that I find it, it's very frightening that these two members are the catalyst behind this motion.

558
00:40:22,706 --> 00:40:24,807
So let me share a few things.

559
00:40:26,488 --> 00:40:31,670
As a member of the council, we had an opportunity to stand up at budget time, didn't we?

560
00:40:32,639 --> 00:40:33,019
Didn't we?

561
00:40:33,220 --> 00:40:33,580
We did.

562
00:40:33,600 --> 00:40:36,062
And three of us stood up and said no.

563
00:40:37,644 --> 00:40:38,825
But some others didn't.

564
00:40:43,389 --> 00:40:52,277
I'll revert to most important thing that bothers me more than anything are the phone calls that I got from the people that work the hardest in our school district.

565
00:40:52,677 --> 00:40:55,420
By the way, majority of them are women.

566
00:40:57,230 --> 00:40:59,352
they're getting their butts kicked.

567
00:40:59,532 --> 00:41:05,817
And what's glaring to this, it's something that we need to turn to our school committee members that's more important than a pay structure.

568
00:41:07,038 --> 00:41:24,373
From what I've heard, and I'm sure we'll hear it tonight, that the possible legalities of lack of coverage in special needs classrooms, lack of coverage with teachers absences, lack of coverage in severely disabled classrooms, that's a problem.

569
00:41:29,457 --> 00:41:34,501
So I'm glad this came up in the sense that this brings something forward.

570
00:41:35,821 --> 00:41:44,407
I think the city council does more, and I think its responsibilities are far more succeeding.

571
00:41:44,668 --> 00:41:47,350
Doesn't mean I'm better than a school kid member at all.

572
00:41:48,230 --> 00:41:57,597
But our responsibilities, our charter, give us the responsibility far greater than our colleagues on the school committee.

573
00:41:59,392 --> 00:42:17,705
And to be honest with you, I'll make a motion later on, whether it's tonight or another night, that since we've cut our time, I'll make the motion if equity, financial equity is serious to the issue, then I would make the motion that we bring the city council pay down so we don't have to.

574
00:42:28,169 --> 00:42:41,617
because Mr. President, Mr. President, again, this city councilor didn't join or didn't ask their constituents to hire, to vote for me so I can make a paycheck.

575
00:42:41,937 --> 00:42:43,558
We're not rich, we're not gonna get rich.

576
00:42:43,939 --> 00:42:51,963
And when everybody ran for their office, when our school committee ran for their office, you're gonna have some candidates that are gonna be stepping in seats that are in the audience tonight.

577
00:42:52,964 --> 00:42:57,207
I'm sure if you ask them, if this was a big concern in their eyes,

578
00:42:58,308 --> 00:43:02,310
they would absolutely flat say, no way, that was not the intention at all.

579
00:43:02,690 --> 00:43:26,084
So I just think that this seems like there's fingerprints with only two spooky members that are pushing an agenda, and I think that this is a sad, sad day when we have unions that don't have contracts, when we have teachers that don't have coverage, and more importantly, please, more importantly, that I find frightening as a former teacher,

580
00:43:26,724 --> 00:43:46,638
that I've talked to a few paraprofessionals, I have two teachers that told me straight out that we have classes, high level, low leveling functioning classes, with special need classrooms, with lack of aids, with lack of certified teachers, and they're just covering them just to have a body in the room, and that's against the law, and that our kids, they don't deserve that.

581
00:43:47,138 --> 00:43:47,939
So that's the biggest issue.

582
00:43:55,919 --> 00:44:01,381
So I know this is going to be left on the next council in January.

583
00:44:01,782 --> 00:44:05,203
But I think it's important that this happens.

584
00:44:05,263 --> 00:44:13,087
These phone calls, these conversations, I think it's great, because I think that's the dialogue we need to move the needle where we need to move it to.

585
00:44:13,787 --> 00:44:16,008
And I'm not going to be critical, but I will to all of you.

586
00:44:17,929 --> 00:44:18,669
Get involved.

587
00:44:19,109 --> 00:44:23,391
Don't come out just when it involves your issue, because that's what we're seeing.

588
00:44:23,731 --> 00:44:24,912
And we can't do that anymore.

589
00:44:26,075 --> 00:44:27,656
So thank you, Mr. President.

590
00:44:28,677 --> 00:44:30,418
Thank you, Councilor Scarpelli.

591
00:44:31,159 --> 00:44:33,701
I do want to say in 2021, we had 85 meetings.

592
00:44:33,841 --> 00:44:35,062
That's when we had weekly meetings.

593
00:44:35,622 --> 00:44:39,185
This year we had 79 meetings, so we have not cut the meetings in half.

594
00:44:39,865 --> 00:44:42,027
I will go to Councilor Seng, Councilor Carvilla.

595
00:44:44,568 --> 00:44:44,789
Okay.

596
00:44:46,630 --> 00:44:49,692
I know many of you all taught me just a few years ago.

597
00:44:52,582 --> 00:44:56,486
I'm sure you'll know that I'm a fan of nuance, but that not everyone's a fan of nuance.

598
00:44:58,088 --> 00:45:00,950
And so I just wanted to preface my remarks with that.

599
00:45:03,873 --> 00:45:07,056
I do actually agree with the principles of this resolution.

600
00:45:07,256 --> 00:45:10,319
I think in execution, we need to tailor it.

601
00:45:10,479 --> 00:45:11,400
We need to improve it.

602
00:45:11,921 --> 00:45:14,843
But I do appreciate that President Morrell has

603
00:45:16,124 --> 00:45:24,926
put out a proposal to address a problem that we have in our city, a can that's been kicked down the road since the year I was born.

604
00:45:26,566 --> 00:45:36,127
And I understand how politically difficult it is for the president to introduce this motion and to take so much flack on it.

605
00:45:37,948 --> 00:45:41,048
It's never easy to discuss the salaries of elected officials.

606
00:45:42,508 --> 00:45:44,909
And whether you agree or disagree with it,

607
00:45:45,769 --> 00:45:54,472
we were always bound to have this conversation at some point, and so I do have to give President Morrell props for having the courage to bring this out.

608
00:45:55,632 --> 00:46:04,495
I also need to note that procedurally, I've heard a lot about, you know, why haven't you talked to other members of the council or other members of the school committee about it?

609
00:46:04,535 --> 00:46:04,935
We do have

610
00:46:05,675 --> 00:46:15,067
laws that govern how we introduce ideas, and the most transparent way to introduce an idea is to put it on the City Council agenda.

611
00:46:15,787 --> 00:46:22,235
It doesn't mean it's going to be passed tonight and it's an ordinance, so it would require three readings anyways.

612
00:46:22,816 --> 00:46:32,288
But usually it's the most transparent approach because we can hear from you, we can hear whether you agree or disagree, we can send it to subcommittee and work on it even more.

613
00:46:33,009 --> 00:46:35,853
And so that's procedurally how it usually works.

614
00:46:38,436 --> 00:46:50,704
I did say I support the principles of this, especially given the fact that school committees being paid a wage or a salary that few in the private sector would ever pay for any job, really.

615
00:46:51,705 --> 00:46:58,749
I'm sympathetic to the argument that school committees and schools in general are seen as female institutions and treated accordingly.

616
00:46:59,009 --> 00:47:03,132
And in other words, there's societal expectations to lower pay outcomes.

617
00:47:03,832 --> 00:47:07,595
And this is really what the crux of the gender pay gap is.

618
00:47:08,435 --> 00:47:15,558
I will say my first reaction to this resolution was, why is the school committee being paid the same as city council?

619
00:47:15,598 --> 00:47:32,125
But I had to reconsider why I even asked that question in the first place, especially given what we know as people who engage with the law, that school committee exercises, you know, city council exercises purview over city hall, which is about

620
00:47:32,685 --> 00:47:37,849
two-thirds of the budget, and the school committee exercises authority over one-third of the city budget.

621
00:47:38,329 --> 00:47:44,454
And in addition, state law does give the school committees many more powers and authorities that we don't have as a city council.

622
00:47:44,954 --> 00:47:52,200
I do know from personal experience, whether you like the job that they're doing or you dislike the job that they're doing, they do spend a lot of hours on their job.

623
00:47:53,390 --> 00:48:13,119
I think in addition to that, as a young person, as a person of color, and as a recent student of social sciences, I know from both my personal experience and from the numerous studies from top researchers that better pay for public officials does increase the quality, diversity, and experience of candidates who run for public office.

624
00:48:14,042 --> 00:48:27,155
Too often, low pay doesn't justify the time that we spend being public officials, and the negativity and hostility of politics in recent years only exacerbates that problem.

625
00:48:28,127 --> 00:48:35,049
Those, you know, we can, I do agree in principle that people running for office should run out of service.

626
00:48:35,089 --> 00:48:53,493
And I, you know, everyone who runs does run out of service, but we can't ignore the economic reality that for people who aren't as economically well off, like students or people of color, we can't just take time out of our days to do political stuff like this instead of working another part-time job.

627
00:48:54,073 --> 00:48:56,454
It's just, it's just economic reality.

628
00:48:57,675 --> 00:49:08,261
We, you know, there are experienced folks who can't justify taking on higher paying projects and research after research shows that government that pays better moves more efficiently.

629
00:49:10,968 --> 00:49:21,990
I hear a lot, and I totally agree with teachers generally, about wanting more young people to run for office, because we have more, especially for school community, because we have more recent experience at the schools.

630
00:49:22,490 --> 00:49:29,232
And it's a reason why I ran for this office in the first place, because the schools, I believe, should be the number one budget issue.

631
00:49:29,752 --> 00:49:35,393
And in the last few budgets, I've sat down with the mayor to negotiate millions more for our schools, successfully.

632
00:49:36,393 --> 00:49:39,674
It's been the number one conversation when I walked into the office.

633
00:49:41,244 --> 00:49:43,228
I just want to know when these discussions happen.

634
00:49:43,548 --> 00:49:45,812
I'll recognize you after Councilor Carvio.

635
00:49:45,852 --> 00:49:46,133
Thank you.

636
00:49:52,392 --> 00:49:57,375
Now, okay, that being said, I am sympathetic to all the ideas in opposition to this.

637
00:49:58,496 --> 00:50:09,404
I've spent a good amount of time these last few days talking to teachers, and I agree in principle that the school committee should pay, should reflect pay increases that teachers get.

638
00:50:09,864 --> 00:50:21,252
Now, we should also keep in mind that the committee hasn't had an increase since 2000, and using a salary calculator, if we compare the percentage increases, this proposal is somewhere in the ballpark of

639
